<HEAD>Water Crew's Kindness Taps Wellspring Of Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POMPANO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bertha </PERSON> <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON> closed her eyes and shuddered as she relived the moment. The 80-year-old widow owed $ 103.44 on her water bill, and city utility truck No. 986 had just arrived at her small, white stucco bungalow to cut off the water. Doing without water would be hard enough for a frail old woman in the suffocating subtropical heat and humidity of south <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, but Mrs. <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON> also cares for a granddaughter who has lost her left leg to diabetes and must undergo kidney dialysis three times a week. `` I tried to explain that somebody had stolen my Social Security check and that I'd pay the bill as soon as my next check came in,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON> told a visiting reporter. `` They told me they were only doing their job. `` It was plain to see those boys did n't want to do it. They said they were real sorry, but it was still awful to watch them drive away and know our water had been cut off.'' But what the crew did next has made the four men local heroes and brought in donations that should make Mrs. <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON> secure for a long time: they drove back, turned the water on and scraped up enough cash to pay her bill. `` When the word got out about what happened, a local plumbing contractor volunteered to pay Mrs. <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON>'s water bill for a year. Another local company is paying her electric bills,'' said <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, who supervises city water department crews. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> and the three members of the city's celebrated utility crew _ <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Craddock </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> _ visited Mrs. <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON> one recent steamy afternoon. They stopped by to say hello and see how she was faring. `` These are my friends,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON> said, giving <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> a hug. `` These fellows are my heroes, they're the ones who started the wheels turning for me.'' The wheels began turning Mrs. <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON>'s way almost immediately after the utility truck pulled away from the curb in front of her house on April 14. `` We decided we just could n't leave her like that,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. `` It was the middle of the month, and that meant it would be more than two weeks before the old lady's next check would arrive. It was plain that she and her granddaughter really needed help.'' Cutting off water service in such a climate makes people desperate, the crew members said. `` Some of them get real nasty and threaten to shoot you or sic their dogs on you,'' said <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>. `` Others get down and beg you not to do it, which only makes it worse.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON> had merely asked for enough time to fill her bathtub and a few pots and pans with water before service was shut off. `` It really touched me,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. So the crew members called their office on the truck radio and found out how much Mrs. <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON> owed. Then they began pulling money out of their pockets. `` <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> and I each put up $ 15 and <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hargrett </PERSON>, our foreman, pitched in $ 20,'' <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said. `` Some other fellows at the office also contributed a few dollars, and <PERSON> Benny </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> put up the remaining $ 33.44.'' <PERSON> Craddock </PERSON> put in a dollar. `` But that was every penny he had,'' said <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>. `` It was a gift from his heart.'' News media soon picked up the story. `` Since then we've gotten dozens of calls and letters from all over the place,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. `` People from as far away as <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> have sent money and checks for Mrs. <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON>; a local guy even stopped by and gave us a check for the $ 103.44 we had put up.'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said he has turned over all the contributions, including the $ 103.44 check, to Mrs. <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON>'s church, where a fund has been set up for her. `` So far, we've received more than $ 700,'' the Rev. <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sample </PERSON>, pastor of the Mt. <ORGANIZATION> Calvary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, said recently. `` We'll use the money to help her pay her bills. Mrs. <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON> lost her husband, <PERSON> Izell </PERSON>, a year ago, and she and her granddaughter, <PERSON> Mercideen </PERSON> <PERSON> Pugh </PERSON>, 37, live on a monthly income of $ 952. Mrs. <PERSON> Shefton </PERSON>, a former domestic worker who cleaned the homes of <LOCATION> Pompano </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>'s more affluent families for 40 years, said she does n't know what to make of all the help and support she has received. `` It's wonderful, but do n't forget that it all started with these boys here,'' she said, pointing to <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, <PERSON> Craddock </PERSON> and <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>. `` We were happy to do it,'' replied <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, who said he, too, is somewhat flabbergasted by all the attention, including letters of commendation from the mayor. `` We did n't have no idea it would turn out like this,'' he said. `` We were just trying to help a nice old lady out of a jam.''
</TEXT>
