<HEAD>Khmer Rouge Claim Victories as 10th Rainy Season Begins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Communist guerrillas fighting in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> said in a broadcast available Sunday that they killed or wounded nearly 3,000 Vietnamese soldiers during May. The claim contradicted earlier pronouncements by <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>, which said fighting had died down and it could therefore begin withdrawing troops. The clandestine <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> radio said 2,821 Vietnamese soldiers had been killed or wounded during the first month of the 10th rainy season of the war. It said <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>'s administrative networks had been dismantled in 537 villages, 11 communes and one township. Past rainy seasons have usually favored the guerrillas, who are fighting the mechanized, conventional forces <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has maintained in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> since its late 1978 invasion. `` They lack both fighting forces and food supplies, and their aggressor soldiers are increasingly demoralized,'' said the broadcast, made available in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. `` In sum, the Vietnamese have failed and are a complete impasse.'' <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, however, has announced that a greatly improved security situation in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> would allow it to pull 50,000 troops out of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> over the next seven months. The partial withdrawal may begin late this month. Western analysts, who are generally skeptical of <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> claims, say there has been a sharp drop in fighting in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in recent months. They speculated that the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> and other guerrilla groups may be stockpiling weapons and positioning themselves for a big push when <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>'s forces are scaled down. The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, ousted from power by the Vietnamese, are allied to two non-communist groups in a loose coalition.
