 For a month, the telephones in the office of Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, have been tied up by members of an anti-pornography group who have been urged to phone him and keep calling `` till you get through.'' Constituents have been unable to reach <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> speaker's staff has had to send a page to contact him and even an exasperated <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> has been kept from reaching his secretary when he's away from the office. About 10,000 calls and nearly 20,000 letters have arrived in a campaign orchestrated by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Tupelo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, which told its members that an anti-pornography bill would die in a subcommittee chaired by <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>. `` Perhaps you believe that a congressional office looks like <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shopping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, with dozens of operators sitting before computer terminals, ready and able to take messages,'' the congressman wrote the Rev. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wildmon </PERSON>, the group's executive director, on May 23, complaining about the tactic, and calling it needless. <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on crime, said the bill is very much alive, and will have a second hearing on Thursday. Any delays have been caused by the diversion of staffers from the bill to work on the letters and phone calls, he said. Callers to <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>' office are now greeted by a recorded message from the seven-term congressman that is on two answering machines. The machines were paid for by members of <PERSON> Hughe