dmon </PERSON> told his followers in early May that the legislation `` is about to die'' in <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>' committee, and urged supporters, `` If his phone is busy, keep calling till you get through.'' The letter said pornographers are `` spending a lot of money, twisting a lot of arms and pressuring a lot of congressmen,'' and asked, `` If you can help defray these unexpected costs, I'd be grateful. You can use the enclosed envelope.'' <PERSON> Wildmon </PERSON> said in an interview that he regrets the inconvenience suffered by <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>' staff, but contended he only wrote the letter after the crime subcommittee staff refused to tell him about plans for the bill. <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> replied that he doubted that allegation, since the staff fields such routine inquiries all the time. Asked what evidence he had that the bill would die in committee, <PERSON> Wildmon </PERSON> said, `` I was told by a number of people who knew what they were talking about.'' Asked who they were he replied, `` No comment.'' He also declined to say how he knew pornographers were pressuring lawmakers. <PERSON> Wildmon </PERSON> denied that the purpose of his letter was to raise money, commenting, `` It cost me $ 79,000 to send the letter. To date, we raised $ 42,000. If I'm going to raise funds by losing $ 37,000 I'm going to be out of business in a hurry. `` It was a two-page letter and there were three sentences of an apology, saying I've got expenses to meet.'' <PERSON> Wildmon </PERSON> said the group had 330,000 supporters, a number based on the 170,000 ministers and 160,000 others who receive the group's publications The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Wildmon </PERSON> said, is a group that `` promotes things that would enhance the family'' and has taken positions against pornography, abortion, and some broadcast entertainment shows.
