<HEAD>Student Gets Laugh During Encounter With Bill Cosby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lori </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoegbauer </PERSON> says the next time she meets comedian <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON> she'll know exactly what to say. `` Oh, my <PERSON> Bill </PERSON>,'' she said, repeating the line <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON> told her after the two met at <LOCATION> Mitchell </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> last week. <PERSON> Stoegbauer </PERSON>, 22, a <ORGANIZATION> Marian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> student, was returning from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on June 8 when a stewardess told her Cosby was on the airplane. <PERSON> Stoegbauer </PERSON>, a longtime Cosby fan, tracked down the comedian in the airport and then screamed, `` Oh my God!'' `` And then he just turned around and said, ` God? I do n't see God anywhere. Who said that?''' <PERSON> Stoegbauer </PERSON> recalled. `` I said I did, and he said, ` Do n't say, ` Oh my God,' say, ` Oh, my Bill.''' <PERSON> Stoegbauer </PERSON> said she recovered enough to shake <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON>'s hand, take his picture and tell him she had fourth-row seats for his show that night at the Marcus Amphitheater in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>. That night at the show, <PERSON> Stoegbauer </PERSON> walked down an aisle right below the stage. Because it was cool in the outdoor theater, she was wearing two sweatshirts with the sleeves pulled down over her hands. Her attire caught <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON>'s attention again. `` He said, ` Hey, you down there,''' <PERSON> Stoegbauer </PERSON> recalled. `` And I said, ` Who, me?' He said, ` Yes, you. Come up here and show everyone how you were just walking.' `` He was in the middle of this big stage, and he had two big video screens on either side of him so everyone could see,'' she added. `` I got up there and he imitated me and just stood there laughing.'' `` I asked him if he remembered me from the airport and he did,'' <PERSON> Stoegbauer </PERSON> said. `` I said, ` Oh my God,' and he said, ` No. Oh, my Bill.' Then he said, ` Thank you. You've been great.'''
