<HEAD>Moderates Battling For Southern Baptist Comeback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Southern Baptists squared off Sunday for another battle over control of the nation's largest <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> denomination, now firmly in the hands of the fundamentalist wing. As thousands of `` messengers'' gathered here for their annual convention, some observers said the moderate camp might make a comeback after nine years of defeat. `` It looks as if moderates could win in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>,'' wrote <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, editor of the `` <ORGANIZATION> SBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cause </ORGANIZATION>,'' urging the other side to bring in voters to avert such an outcome. Convention business begins Tuesday after a day of preliminary meetings and preaching. Up to 40,000 people are expected to attend as representatives of the church's 14.7 million members. The conflict in the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION>, as the denomination is known, has intensified over the last year as increased fundamentalist power drove various leaders out of office and imposed tighter rules of belief. The struggle, fought largely over the issue of whether the Bible is the literal truth, has stirred up bitter feelings and sharp words. `` Clever men have stripped us of our rights,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baugh </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> businessman and layman of the moderate camp. Fundamentalism, he said, brings out an `` insatiable appetite for power and demand for conformity.'' `` It's time to stop this nonsense of barbarian attacks on that which we hold dear.'' A pro-fundamentalist former convention president, the Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Draper </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Euless </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, said after a recent clash with a moderate leader: `` It seems to be a situation of who can outmuscle the other. They have given us no alternative.'' A man in the middle, the Rev. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Roanoke </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, who for three years has headed a peace committee trying to calm the turmoil, said the denomination is `` in a crisis of spirit.'' The peace plan, he said, has been repeatedly violated and there has been an `` acceleration of political activity'' by both sides with partisan strategy meetings held in numerous states. At the center of the conflict is the denomination's powerful presidency, which has the authority to appoint trustees who control Southern Baptist agencies and institutions. Most of those boards now have fundamentalist majorities as a result of the wing's nine years of presidential victories. The crucial decision at this week's meeting is election of a new president. The two camps have rallied behind the expected opposing nominees, and campaigns for them have rolled across the country. Backed by the fundamentalist wing is the Rev. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Vines </PERSON>, co-pastor of the 18,000-member <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jacksonville </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>. The expected moderate nominee is the Rev. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, pastor of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phoenix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, also with 18,000 members. Both are fundamentalists in their views of the Bible, whose interpretation has been at the crux of the struggle, but <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> does n't favor imposing his view on institutional trustees, while Vines does. `` I would not appoint anyone to any committee,'' <PERSON> Vines </PERSON> said, `` who did not endorse'' prescriptions laid down by the peace committee. It insists the Bible is without error and on belief in its text as literal truth _ that <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> and Eve were real people, that the biblical miracles actually occurred, and that the Bible accurately records history. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, `` I do n't believe there ought to be a control group,'' and that if he wins election, it would mean `` a change to allow Baptists to be free again.'' The winner will succeed the Rev. <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, a fundamentalist standard-bearer who has held the post a customary two years. His previous election in 1979 inaugurated the fundamentalist tide.
