<TEXT>
 Two years ago, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Stimpfle </PERSON> would stand on the beach in <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> and release balloons to float across the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION>, hoping to help thaw a Cold War ban on travel between <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>. People laughed and called him crazy. But on Monday, <PERSON> Stimpfle </PERSON> will take off on a flight to <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, accompanied by 80 politicians, <PERSON> Eskimos </PERSON> and reporters, crossing a border that has been closed for 40 years. `` There was a lot of skepticism at first,'' <PERSON> Stimpfle </PERSON> recalled Thursday from <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION>, in a telephone interview often interrupted by calls from the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> governor's office and others helping to plan Monday's `` Friendship Flight'' to the Siberian city of <LOCATION> Provideniya </LOCATION>. `` There were a lot of people who thought it would n't happen in our lifetime,'' <PERSON> Stimpfle </PERSON> said. `` There were a lot of people who thought I was eccentric and questioned my loyalty and my motivations.'' The real estate agent says his motivations are simple: Two years ago, at the start of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s oil recession, business was slow and he had time to think up ways of improving his own fortune and that of <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION>, a town of 3,700 people on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s western coast. <PERSON> Stimpfle </PERSON>, 40, figured that if someone could pry open the <LOCATION> Alaska-Siberia </LOCATION> border, closed in 1948 because of Cold War tensions, then <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> could become an economic center for both sides of the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION>. He envisioned increased trade, joint economic ventures, and tourist excursions by airplanes and cruise ships between <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Siberia </L