vember. The biggest break came last fall, when <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jumped on the `` Friendship Flight'' bandwagon, hoping to establish a regular tourist route, he said. Government officials who brushed off a real estate agent's letters about flights to <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> began getting similar letters from executives of a major corporation. `` As long as just one person was doing it, it never would have reached this level of credibility,'' <PERSON> Stimpfle </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Stimpfle </PERSON> would like to see the whole <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> border opened. He would like to see more joint ventures in fishing, telecommunications, and trade. Many who once scoffed at his dreams now give him the benefit of the doubt. `` It was only a short while ago that this flight was a dream,'' said <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Cancelmi </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. `` I personally wondered if this day would ever come. `` I do n't think <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Stimpfle </PERSON> ever thought for a moment that it would n't, and that's what it takes to make something like this come true.''
