<SECOND>AM-Drought-Mississippi,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mississippi River Nearing Record Lows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICKSBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The mighty <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> could hit record low levels this summer because of the drought plaguing the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, and already has fallen enough in places to ground barges, officials say. The river stood at just 8 feet on the <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION> gauge on May 28, the second-lowest reading on record for that date. By Friday, it had fallen to 3.8 feet, and it was expected to fall to 3 feet by Monday and continue dropping. Monday's predicted reading would be the record low for this time of year _ about 30 feet below normal. The lowest reading at <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION> for any date was in the early 1930s when the river dropped to minus 6.7 feet below the level considered as the zero point. At <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, the river could sink below the 7 -LCB- - year-old record of minus 7.3 feet by July 13, according to a 28-day forecast released by the <ORGANIZATION> Lower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forecast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Slidell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> `` The river is still very deep and dangerous, but this is a record low,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Logue </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION>' <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>. In some areas, the river remains deeper than 100 feet, <PERSON> Logue </PERSON> said. But many points along the boat traffic channel have fallen below the minimum 9-foot depth needed for normal navigation. That means big problems for towboat operators who must lighten cargoes and run the risk of equipment damage if they run aground. <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Radlein </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forecasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Slidell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, said it would take heavy rainfall over a large part of the central <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to raise the river appreciably. And that's not likely this time of year. `` The types of stages we're reporting now are similar to what you'd normally get in late September, after a hot, dry summer,'' she said. `` And we've still got that ahead of us.'' Normally, this would be the high water season, <PERSON> Logue </PERSON> said, but the <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> expects to have to dredge soon near <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION> to keep the channel open. `` It looks like it's going to be a major challenge this year to maintain our navigation project,'' <PERSON> Logue </PERSON> said. `` I'm sure the economic impact is in the millions of dollars already from people having to carry shallow loads. It has an impact on the whole central part of the country.'' <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Golding </PERSON>, owner of <LOCATION> Ole </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Man </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Towing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION>, said the drought has cut into his profits. <LOCATION> Ole </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Man </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> is loading barges for a draft of 8.6 feet rather than the normal 9.6 feet, `` and that last foot sometimes is your only profit margin,'' <PERSON> Golding </PERSON> said. Current cargoes generally are about 10 to 15 percent lighter, he said. The cost of pushing the load is the same or higher, because trips take longer, <PERSON> Golding </PERSON> said. Maintenance costs are higher because of problems with running aground, he said. <PERSON> Golding </PERSON> said the navigable channel is so narrow in places that northbound tows must wait downstream for southbound towboats to pass. Last weekend, 55 barges ran aground at <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, closing that stretch of the river for two days while the tows were disassembled and moved. Friday, the river was reopened from <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> for the first time in two days after numerous tows ran aground. The Red River, a <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> tributary of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, is closed indefinitely, with some boats stranded upstream. `` It makes for an unpredictable trip,'' <PERSON> Golding </PERSON> said. `` And it puts a lot of stress on the pilots. Last week, we ran aground with one barge and knocked a hole in the bottom. We also knocked a rudder off one of our boats.''
