<HEAD>Government Launches Ad Campaign Promoting Local Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two days after banning calls for election boycotts, the government Sunday launched an advertising campaign to promote participation in municipal elections scheduled for October. Full-page newspaper ads urged <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africans </LOCATION> to `` let your vote speak for you'' in the nationwide elections Oct. 26. `` Vote for a better life for yourself and those who are dear to you,'' said another ad. `` Let the people of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> be heard.'' It will be the first time South Africans of all races go to the polls on the same day. They will be voting for more than 7,000 seats on municipal councils in their racially segregated communities. Most anti-apartheid organizations in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, as well as the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement, oppose black participation in any elections until the black majority is granted full political rights at the national level. The black <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> movement is fighting the government's policy of apartheid, which establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The government, while describing itself as `` pro-democracy,'' says it will never accept a one-person, one-vote system that would allow the blacks to overrule the 5 million whites. On Friday, when it extended a national state of emergency for a third year, the government imposed a new regulation outlawing calls for boycotts of elections, except by a registered political party competing in an election. The far-right <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which opposes even limited concessions to blacks, charged that the $ 2.3 million ad campaign constitutes use of taxpayers' money to spread propaganda on behalf of President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. A confidential outline of the ad campaign, disclosed by a <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader who obtained a copy, said the government's public credibility was not good. An advertising agency suggested in the document that animated cartoon characters be used in television ads to promote voting, because direct communication from the government might be `` unacceptable to the public.'' Information Minister <PERSON> Stoffel </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Merwe </PERSON> defended the campaign last week, saying it was not partisan. `` It is pro-democracy and anti-revolutionary, for which we do not apologize,'' he said. The ads published Sunday exhorted voters to `` vote for the candidate who will best look after your interests.'' The white municipal elections will provide the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> with another chance to gain strength at the expense of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The Conservatives won three parliamentary by-elections earlier this year, and they predict a sweep of local elections in towns and small cities throughout <LOCATION> Transvaal </LOCATION> province in the north, where more than half of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s whites live. The key question in the black municipal elections is whether the government can prevent disruptions by militants and persuade a significant number of candidates to participate, despite the likelihood that these will be depicted as apologists for the government. Defense Minister <PERSON> Magnus </PERSON> <PERSON> Malan </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> last month that `` radicals and revolutionaries ... regard the elections as a prime target for disruption and intimidation.'' `` It is my duty and your duty to ensure that these elections are a success,'' he told lawmakers.
