<HEAD>Police Withdrawn From Toxic Waste Site For Safety</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police guarding a site where European toxic waste was secretly dumped withdrew after chemists confirmed the material was poisonous, the <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nigeria </ORGANIZATION> said Sunday. Assistant police inspector <PERSON> Aminu </PERSON> <PERSON> Malumfashi </PERSON> said they left the site in <LOCATION> Bendel </LOCATION> state for their own safety, the agency said. They had sealed off the area to keep the public away. The military government announced Saturday that preliminary tests of waste show the substances to be poisonous. Scientists urged that all people who visited the area undergo medical tests. The waste, which included radioactive material, was dumped near the town of <LOCATION> Koko </LOCATION>, 150 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION>. The dumping episode, the latest in a series of alleged efforts by European and American companies to dump hazardous waste in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, has strained relations between <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> has recalled its ambassador to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> and demanded that an Italian ship remove the waste, which had been imported by an Italian company working for 10 European firms. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> has said it is cooperating in an investigation. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, whose honorary consul general in <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> was arrested for complicity in the dumping of waste there, said the waste would be returned to <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. On May 31, five Congolese, including three senior government officials, were charged with plotting to secretly import toxic waste for dumping there.
