<HEAD>Friend Says He Paid $6,000 For Speaker's Books</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wright Ethics Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A longtime friend of House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> says he paid <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> $ 6,000 for copies of his books as a legal way to get around federal limits on campaign contributions. <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> developer <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Payte </PERSON>, who has known <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> since he entered <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1955, told the <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star-Telegram </ORGANIZATION> he bought 1,000 copies of the book to `` show my appreciation.'' Federal election laws limit individual campaign contributions to $ 1,000 for each election. <PERSON> Payte </PERSON> said knew about the limit but wanted to find a way to boost <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s income, the <ORGANIZATION> Star-Telegram </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday. `` If I wanted to help <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> and wanted to give him some money, I could n't do it,'' he said. `` But I could buy his books.'' <PERSON> Payte </PERSON> also said he wrote letters to nearly 50 <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worth </ORGANIZATION> businessmen urging them each to buy $ 1,000 worth of the books, but did not know if they followed up on the request. He would not name them. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> decided last week to conduct a inquiry to determine if <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> has violated rules on ethics and conflicts of interest. One aspect of the inquiry will be the publication arrangements for his 1984 book `` Reflections of a Public Man.'' <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> orthodontist <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, another longtime <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> friend, said he paid $ 1,000 to publisher <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> after <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> told him he was trying to put together a group of about 20 people to finance republication of the book last year. `` I paid to have some republished and a big box -LRB- of books -RRB- was sent to me,'' <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> said. He added that he had already given <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> the maximum $ 1,000 in campaign contributions. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> has acknowledged that some supporters bought large numbers of books, but said it was n't an attempt to get around contribution limits. `` I think that's a mistake,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think anybody really thought that.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> instead said, `` I'm glad they thought enough of the book.'' Meanwhile, another longtime <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> friend of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said he was present when <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> asked a congressional aide if he would `` sacrifice a couple of weekends'' to work on the book. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Procter </PERSON>, professor of history at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, located in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, recalled the request in a sworn statement <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> provided the ethics committee Friday. One charge the committee will investigate is whether <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> paid the aide, <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Cossolotto </PERSON>, $ 2,000 in public money to help compile the book. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ethics manual says congressional employees may not be paid from public funds to perform personal or campaign activities on behalf of a congressman.
