<HEAD>Decaturs Of The World Compete To Raise Food For The Needy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 City officials have learned the answer to the question on their promotional T-shirts: `` Where the heck's Decatur? There's a <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> almost everywhere, from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> _ 28 at last count. And the smaller Decaturs have accepted the challenge of the largest to collect food for the poor and put themselves on the map. Local organizers created `` Cans Across The Country'' to see which <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> could collect the most food and provide it to hungry people in each of the communities. The goal is one can of food for each resident _ a potential of about 200,000 cans. `` The real winners will be the recipients of the food,'' said <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewellen </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Decatur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advantage </ORGANIZATION>, an organization that promotes the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> city of about 94,000 residents. `` But every <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> that participates will be a winner because a grass-roots movement with volunteers working for a common good generates a spirit of unity. That makes a community stronger,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Lewellen </PERSON> initially identified nine other cities of <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> and two <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> counties, and Mayor <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> mailed a white glove to each to begin the competition Memorial Day weekend. The official T-shirt of the contest has a <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> map on the front. The question mark in `` Where the heck's Decatur?'' rests in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. But, as word of the contest spread across the country, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> officials realized their count of 12 Decaturs was short. `` This little town of <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> called,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Lewellen </PERSON>. `` Decatur townships surfaced. There's even one in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, population 20, except in the summer when it's 100 Many of them do n't even have a zip code.'' Her count rose to 25. The <ORGANIZATION> Decatur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Review did some additional research and identified 28 Decaturs. `` I'm not sure we're through finding Decaturs yet,'' said the mayor. `` But, the more the merrier.'' All are welcome in the contest, which has has been divided into three divisions based on population. There are no prizes, said the mayor, `` just satisfaction and pride.'' Officials from all the Decaturs will be invited to the opening ceremony of Decatur Celebration here Aug. 5. The winners will be announced then, although some <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> officials figure they have victory wrapped up. `` There's no doubt in my mind,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. `` We've never been beaten at anything. I'll be there to pick up my first-place trophy and to bring y' all some chili and jalapeno peppers. The mayor of <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, promised <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> a consolation prize of a pinto bean-and-peanut butter sandwich, and Mayor <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukes </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, said schoolchildren brought 7,000 cans of food in just one day, and `` we're going to beat <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said the contest will increase public awareness about all of the Decaturs _ communities named for <PERSON> Commodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <