<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A special commission created by Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> called Sunday for cuts in federal spending, consideration of tax increases and a longer school year to deal with what it says is the country's economic crisis. The <ORGANIZATION> Cuomo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Competitiveness </ORGANIZATION> said the nation's leaders should consider a freeze on military spending; taxing Social Security benefits of wealthier Americans; and a reduction of farm subsidies that benefit large producers. The commission also recommmended higher taxes for luxury items and consideration of a $ 10-per-barrel oil import fee and the imposition of a value-added tax on goods and services. The commission said that, if adopted, both the oil import fee and the value-added tax should be structured to insulate the poor. `` The commission believes that future fiscal policy must be based on a combination of reduced spending and increased revenue,'' said the 259-page report from the 20-member task force that included businessmen, labor leaders and economists. The <ORGANIZATION> Cuomo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Report is being published as a paperback by <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> and Schuster and will be available in book stores as early as Monday, said <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowley </PERSON>. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, once considered a potential 1988 Democratic presidential candidate, has been pushing economic reform for months. In addition to creating the <ORGANIZATION> Cuomo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in January 1987, the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> governor led the drive for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which was approved by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in December. The commission, which is due to report after the November election, is headed by former <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> and <PERSON> Republican </PERSON> <PERSON> Drew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> secretary of transportation. Other members include <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> financier <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Rohatyn </PERSON>. The national commission is to prepare recommendations on the national deficit, trade imbalance, Third World debt and productivity _ the same issues dealt with by the <ORGANIZATION> Cuomo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. `` The word ` crisis' has been cheapened by too frequent use, but no other word so well describes <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s present situation,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Cuomo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> concluded. `` Either <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will implement reforms that strengthen the international trading system and make the nation more competitive at home or it risks a long, slow national decline.'' The major problems facing the nation on the economic front are the trade deficit and the federal deficit, according to the commission. The commission said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must improve its production capabilities, in part through greater employee participation; work to improve living conditions and create new markets in the Third World by, among other things, helping restructure debt payments for developing nations; and stabilize the international monetary system. Repairing roads and bridges was given a high priority by the group as was giving the nation's youth the tools with which to compete. `` We need a longer school year,'' said the commission. `` Japanese students attend school 240 days a year, European students, on average, 220 days. In the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, the average school year is 180 days. ... The shorter school year clearly places <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> students at an educational disadvantage.''
