<HEAD>Worldwide AIDS Cases Expected To Double This Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AIDS Meeting, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An estimated 150,000 people will develop AIDS this year, doubling the number of estimated AIDS cases worldwide since the epidemic began, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> said Sunday. `` AIDS is changing the world,'' said <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>'s AIDS program. `` It has become a key part of the history of our time.'' He spoke at the opening session of the <ORGANIZATION> Fourth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on AIDS in <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>. The number of AIDS cases officially reported to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> stood at 75,392 on Jan. 12 and 96,433 as of June 1. The number of actual cases is estimated to be 200,000, <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> said. Although AIDS was not identified until 1981, the origins of the epidemic have been traced back to the 1970s. `` A virus spread across the world, and we did n't even know it existed,'' <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> said. `` It is _ or should be _ shocking to our modern pride that such a global expansion could occur without even being detected.'' <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> said the five years after 1981 marked a period of extraordinary discovery, in which the ways in which AIDS spread were identified, the virus was isolated and an AIDS antibody test was developed. <PERSON> Lars </PERSON> <PERSON> Kallings </PERSON>, chairman of the AIDS conference, said the meeting allowed scientists to assemble their findings, like the pieces of a jigsaw puzzle, into a large picture of the AIDS epidemic. `` I'm afraid that the picture in its entirety will be frightening,'' he said. <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> described the three distinct patterns of AIDS spread that make up the worldwide epidemic. Pattern I, he said, is that seen in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where the disease appeared first in homosexuals and bisexuals. Heterosexual transmission is growing in those areas, the virus is spreading rapidly among drug abusers through their shared needles, but blood supplies have now been made safe by screening for the virus. Pattern II, <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> said, characterizes <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, where the AIDS spread has been predominantly among heterosexuals. Pattern III refers to the delayed spread of AIDS in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and most countries in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. Only 1 percent of the AIDS cases reported to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> come from Pattern III countries, <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> said. Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a disease in which a virus attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to a wide variety of infections and cancers.
