<HEAD>Genscher Welcomes Soviet Arms Reduction Statement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> welcomes a Soviet suggestion on a conventional arms treaty with the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> but only as a starting point for future negotiations, <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>'s spokesman said Sunday. `` This will have to be looked at very closely, but it does show a new thinking in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' spokesman <PERSON> Juergen </PERSON> <PERSON> Chrobog </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. He was referring to remarks by Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> last week in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> indicating the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact alliance was ready to make cuts in its conventional forces that would not have to be matched equally by the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. At a conference on <ORGANIZATION> East-West </ORGANIZATION> security Saturday in <LOCATION> Potsdam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> said he greeted the apparent change in the Kremlin's position. `` This speech in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> -LRB- by <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> -RRB- is welcomed because now it has been clearly stated that everywhere there is an -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- advantage, asymmetrical cuts will have to be made,'' <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> said at the three-day conference that ended Saturday. `` This is very important for us in view of the superiority by the Eastern side in large-scale equipment -LRB- such as tanks -RRB-,'' he added. Earlier in the <LOCATION> Potsdam </LOCATION> conference, other Soviet officials said the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact was ready to make asymmetrical cuts in its tank force, but they linked such reductions with elimination of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s advantages in fighter aircraft and attack helicopters <PERSON> Chrobog </PERSON> said <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> was pleased with the Soviet statements on conventional arms `` but these are matters which we have to analyze further'' along with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies. During the <LOCATION> Potsdam </LOCATION> conference the Soviet deputy foreign minister, <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Aboymov </PERSON>, outlined the latest Soviet proposals calling for a three-stage reduction of conventional forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. He said the first stage would be an elimination of force imbalances between <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact, followed by a reduction of 500,000 troops on each side and then restructuring the remaining forces to give them a defensive rather than offensive capability.
