<TEXT>
 A woman trapped in the collapse of a cave from which two male companions escaped was found dead early Sunday, and a fire official said dry weather may have contributed to the collapse. Crews using shovels and backhoes found the body of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION>, 23, of <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON>, in the rubble of the cave in a sandstone cliff near the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> on the city's southeast side. Recent dry weather may have contributed to Saturday night's accident in <LOCATION> Battle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, said District Fire Chief <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, referring to the fine, powdery rubble of disintegrated sandstone <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, 21, of <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, said the three were sitting in the cave listening to a tape player when the accident occurred. `` I was in the mouth of the cave. Sand started coming, and I heard rumbling and started running,'' <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said from <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul-Ramsey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. `` Something hit me in the head. My legs were completely buried under sand and rock.'' He said <PERSON> Green </PERSON> was deeper in the cave but that he was not sure why she did n't run out. <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> suffered an ankle injury. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sederstrom </PERSON>, 22, of <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, said he escaped without injury.
