<FIRST>r a AM-FuzzyDirections     06-12 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fuzzy Directions,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tufts Design Engineers Trying to Clear Up ``Fuzzy Directions''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Product directions often seem simple. `` Press firmly'' is a typical instruction. But how firmly? Design engineers at <ORGANIZATION> Tufts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> are researching ways to make such orders more specific. They began after learning that owners of homes with a certain kind of gas valve were asked to test them by pressing a knob firmly without forcing it; with no more than those directions, the owners were expected to determine whether their valves were defective and possibly dangerous. `` The goal of the research is the ability to craft phrases that will produce well-defined physical responses,'' said Professor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kreifeldt </PERSON>. A graduate student in design engineering at <ORGANIZATION> Tufts </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Kodali </LOCATION> <LOCATION> V.N </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rao </PERSON>, developed an experiment to see if product directions could be made more simple. `` From nail polish to computers, cameras to hair sprays and toasters to tanks, the designer needs to be well-informed about the consequences resulting from use or misuse of the product,'' said <PERSON> Rao </PERSON>. `` As designers, we have to decide that a switch should work with a certain amount of force.'' But how does one go about communicating that, he wondered. In his research, he asked about 240 people to squeeze a device attached to a meter, either gently or hard. The results varied considerably. The instruction `` firm'' covered a range of two kilograms to 32 kilograms of force. The project's most surprising result: when the instructions were changed to `` squeeze not very hard and not too gently,'' the test participants were remarkably consistent. Ninety percent of the participants applied 12.9 to 14.6 kilograms of force. <PERSON> Rao </PERSON> said that the word `` not'' in instructions causes people to be more cautious about how much pressure they exert. `` Force is a perceivable thing that people can use through experience,'' said <PERSON> Rao </PERSON>. `` One thing is sure: one-word instructions do n't convey enough information. If you say ` Do this,' people tend to get carried away by presuppositions, so it is important to give users parameters.''
</TEXT>
