<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITFIELD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As many as 60 children may have eluded social workers who rounded up and removed residents of a boarding home under investigation for abuse, the state <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> chief said Sunday. But state Welfare Commissioner <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said he was unsure how many children may have been left behind when students from the <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> Home for Children near <LOCATION> Lucedale </LOCATION> were removed Friday by the workers armed with a court order. `` There are still a whole lot of kids out there wandering around somewhere that were released through a totally inappropriate manner,'' <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said at a Sunday news conference. He said 66 children had been taken into custody, including a runaway brought to a state mental institution, early Sunday morning. The children were rounded up near the campus of the 28-acre home, at restaurants and along roadways. Even as welfare workers continued trying to reunite some of the youngsters with their familes, the Rev. <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON>, the home's operator, said he was sheltering four or five youngsters who fled the home before the workers arrived `` I've still got a few soldiers left, and I'm trying to work back to what it was before,'' said <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON>, 38, who established the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> home 10 years ago as what he calls a last refuge for troubled kids. <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> says he is a former heroin addict, and his experiences on the streets of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> qualify him to work with such children. Fountain's comments drew a tight-lipped response from the judge who ordered the <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to remove children from the home that has come under criticism intermittently since 1980. `` I'll deal with it, but I'll deal with it Monday,'' Chancery Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Oswald </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from his home. A court hearing is set for Monday morning in <LOCATION> Lucedale </LOCATION> to decide where the children taken from <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> will be placed. <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said `` between 10 and 15'' children already had been released to their parents. The commissioner said he was satisfied with the state's handling of the situation and was not worried that some parents might want to sue the state for removing the children. <PERSON> Oswald </PERSON> ruled Friday that children at <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> _ who range in age from 10 to 17 and are mostly from outside <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> _ were subjected `` to physical abuse, medical neglect and detention amounting to imprisonment.'' He ordered their immediate removal. <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON>, who supervised the children's removal from the home, said Saturday that medical examinations of some children showed excessive use of corporal punishment. As for the children who have returned to <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> since Friday, <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said, `` We'll work with the court on that and follow the court's direction on that.'' There have been estimates that 120 to 160 children were at the home. Fountain refused to provide the court a list with names and addresses of the children and their parents. Fountain vowed Saturday in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Lucedale </LOCATION> to continue to keep open <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>'s doors and said he had taken in another resident, a teen-age boy, despite the judge's Friday order. `` To tell you the truth, I do n't know how that court order reads,'' he said. Charges that he enslaved and beat children are half-truths, <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> said. The children were brought to him precisely because they needed strong discipline and hard work to set them on a spiritual path. `` The parents have lost control. Kids today are such manipulators. Such cons. Especially a child from a divorce. They've learned how to manipulate their parents,'' the independent Baptist minister said `` The children are here mainly for runaways, stealing, homosexuality. We have little girls who were whores,'' he said. `` They need a little discipline, a little bit of hard work. We give them the Bible, not that trash they read, not rock' n' roll. They are going to do work when they are here.'' Fountain believes the state welfare department is in conspiracy against him, a conspiracy that runs so deep, those involved are unaware. The conspiracy is based on the principles of humanism, an anathema to his own fundamentalist beliefs and his advocacy of separation between church and state, he claims. The conspiracy's aim, he said, is to set up licensing laws for church-run homes, something he insists he will never submit to.
