<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Presidential candidate <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on Sunday called President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s anti-drug programs `` chaos'' and promised the nation's mayors a tough program to curb drug use and trafficking that would include the possible use of military force. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor, who has enough delegates to secure the Democratic presidential nomination, called for stronger drug laws and stringent sentencing guidelines, but stopped short of endorsing capital punishment for major dealers, which apparent Republican nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> supports. `` My friends, we can win the war against drugs,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION>, where he picked up endorsements from more than 500 Democratic mayors. `` But we have to recognize that it is war _ a war of wills, a war of values, a war of confidence and courage and strength,'' he said in his speech to the mayors. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> also reiterated his pledge to raise taxes only as a last resort, and told the mayors he welcomed their suggestions on potential running mates. `` A lot of people are going to be considered,'' he told reporters prior to the speech. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> touted a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> program that brings drug education to students and teachers and involves police and local celebrities, promising to establish a similar national program if elected. He said a national program should have the goal of ridding the nation's schools of drugs by the 1990s and guaranteeing immediate treatment for addicts. `` Now some may say that goal is too ambitious, that we'll never make it,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` But if we do n't set ambitious goals for our young people and for our nation, how are we ever going to win this war?'' In a scathing indictment of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s anti-drug effort, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said the president has failed to back up his tough rhetoric and has undermined the war on drugs by cutting the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> budget, by slashing federal aid to state and local police, by failing to appoint a federal drug Czar, and by dealing with suspected drug runners _ particularly <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. `` What we have today is chaos,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` We've got to back up what we say with what we do.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> promised the mayors to beef up federal law enforcement staffs and to increase federal aid to state and local police, although he did not suggest a specific dollar amount when asked by reporters. He also said, `` We've got to move the war against narcotics from the bottom to the top of our foreign policy agenda.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said that if elected he would issue an executive order prohibiting the payment of <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> or other government funds to suspected drug dealers. `` Never again, never again are you going to bankroll a drug peddler who is poisoning our society and killing are children,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. He also said he would use increased amounts of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign aid for crop eradication and other drug interdiction efforts, including the protection of politicians, police and judges in drug-producing countries whose lives are threatened by drug kingpins. The military should be prepared to assist in such efforts, said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who again did not provide specific dollar figures on the foreign aid proposal. `` It will take tough, sustained and unrelenting enforcement, on the ground, in the air and at sea _ at home and abroad,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` Enforcement which uses the military where appropriate and necessary.'' He also chided <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for not working with Latin American leaders to oust <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, saying such cooperation was vital to stopping the flow of cocaine and marijuana into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. After his speech, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> met with <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> mayors and later was holding a private session with a smaller group of black mayors. He was returning to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> Sunday night and was to meet Monday with congressional leaders and law enforcement officials from several states to discuss drug issues.
