<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A proposed major Presbyterian statement on nuclear war was revised Sunday to say a Christian `` normally'' should support the government and nuclear deterrence is immoral `` as an end in inself.'' A writing team working over the weekend on `` Christian Obedience in a Nuclear Age'' made the changes, which a subcommittee then adopted. The changes will be presented to a full committee Monday, and the 200th <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> of the Presbyterian Church -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION> -RRB- is scheduled to take up the paper Tuesday. Also on the agenda when 630 delegates of the nation's largest Presbyterian body return to work Monday are the election of a top denominational officer and a host of other issues, including pornography, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s treatment of Palestinians in occupied territories and religious freedom. The subcommittee of 18 people, including lay, clergy, youth and seminary advisory delegates, generally adopted the work of the writing committee Sunday. The writing panel had been charged with making the paper's policy statement and background agree with the revised recommendations made by the subcommittee earlier Those changes included removing language that would strengthen corporate church support for tax resisters and other government protesters and soften language declaring nuclear deterrence immoral. The changes shifted some words to play down discussion of tax resistance and added language saying Christian obedience to civil authority `` is normally the case.'' A paragraph was also added recognizing military service as a legitimate Christian response. The revised policy statement also retains condemnation of nuclear war as immoral. But the original declaration of nuclear deterrence as being immoral was altered to add the phrase `` as an end in itself.'' The proposed policy statement now says: `` The policy of nuclear deterrence has been in danger of becoming an end in itself rather than an interim measure of self-defense. Such a policy as an end in itself is not morally defensible. The work for peaceful alternatives needs to be vigorously pursued.'' Supporters of the initial paper said they expect the full assembly <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peacemaking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> to restore some of the original language. While opponents of the paper agreed that was possible, `` whatever they do to the document, it needs to be sent for prayerful consideration'' by the church instead of adopted as a policy, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON>, president of Presbyterians for Democracy and Religious Freedom. A nominating committee's decision not to include an incumbent as a candidate for a top denominational office caught the assembly by surprise Saturday afternoon. There were indications commissioners would face a contested election when they vote Tuesday. The Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>, 60, has been stated clerk or interim co-stated clerk of the denomination since it was formed in 1983 by the reunion of the Northern and Southern branches of the Presbyterian church. Previously, he held the same office in the Presbyterian Church -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> -RRB-, the Southern church, for 10 years. The committee nominated <PERSON> Harriet </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, a popular former moderator _ or chief spokesman _ for the $ 62,000-a-year job. <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> has said his name will be placed in nomination from the assembly floor when voting begins. In addition, the Rev. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurst </PERSON>, a local church executive from <LOCATION> Pompano </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, will be nominated from the floor. Other committee recommendations include a call for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to end its 20-year occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> asked to stop sending aid which is used to subsidize Israeli settlement of the territories.
