<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> and the other gorillas in a new `` rain forest'' at <LOCATION> Zoo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> seemed to take it in stride when the general public was admitted to the attraction for the first time. Thousands of people streamed into the Ford African Rain Forest after a ribbon-cutting ceremony Saturday to strain for a look at Willie B., the zoo's biggest star, in the lush open-air habitat which replaced the cage he occupied for 27 years. The 450-pound gorilla, now about 30 years old, immediately came to the edge of a restraining moat to strut for the crowd; once, he ran down a grassy slope, drawing applause. On each side, across moats, two families of gorillas recently brought to the zoo kept a greater distance from onlookers but remained mostly in the open and not in their shelters. Zoo Director <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Maple </PERSON> said the gorillas, while physically separated, have interacted in the 2 -LCB- weeks they have been together. `` They're vocalizing, they're beating their chests, they're moving this way and influencing the others,'' Maple said `` The behavior of animals is enhanced by the presence of others.'' Zoo Business Manager <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said a record for paid attendance at the zoo was set Saturday, and broken Sunday. Sunday's crowd was 11,860, with 10,893 paid, passing the mark of 8,522 set Saturday, when there were also nearly 5,000 free admissions The zoo's best attendance was 17,000 in 1986 when there was free admission to celebrate <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> B </PERSON>.'s birthday, but the record paid attendance before Saturday was about 7,400, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. The four-acre, $ 4.5 million rain forest, boosted by $ 1 million donated by the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, is the centerpiece of a renovation of the 99-year-old zoo, dubbed one of the 10 worst in the country by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> only four years ago. Three gorilla families, including the two already present, are being provided by the <ORGANIZATION> Yerkes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Primate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The exhibit includes an adjacent aviary, featuring birds from the same areas of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> inhabited by the gorillas. It is the second of 10 habitats planned; a flamingo habitat opened first. Next year, <PERSON> Maple </PERSON> said, the zoo will present an east African savanna, featuring lions and elephants and including a pool deep enough for an elephant to immerse itself.
