<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRNAVA, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some 15,000 people packed inside and around a church applauded <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> demands Sunday that the communist government permit more Roman Catholic bishops and priests. In the first ceremony of its kind since 1973, <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> representative Archbishop <PERSON> Francesco </PERSON> <PERSON> Colasuonno </PERSON> consecrated <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sokol </PERSON> as a bishop and apostolic administrator of the archdiocese of <LOCATION> Trnava </LOCATION>. The archdiocese is known as the `` Rome of <LOCATION> Slovakia </LOCATION>'' because of its many historic churches. In a 20-minute sermon interrupted at least two dozen times by applause, <PERSON> Colasuonno </PERSON> called for bishops to fill the vacancies in nine of the nation's 13 dioceses and more religious education. `` Religious life must regain its full rights in a secular society,'' he said. `` Only if it has its rightful place can it contribute to the progress and welfare of the citizens.'' The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> emissary indicated Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> wants much more than the authorities' approval of the appointment of <PERSON> Sokol </PERSON> and of two assistant bishops who were consecrated in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> on Saturday. `` We hope that the negotiatons of the Holy See with all bodies... will bring further results,'' said <PERSON> Colasuonno </PERSON>, speaking in Slovak Negotiations between the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> and government are continuing. `` This work ... should not end with the appointment of bishops, but should go much further,'' he said. After his consecration the 54-year-old <PERSON> Sokol </PERSON> said, `` I am sure that this was the first step and that others will follow. The vacant bishops' sees will soon be filled with good bishops according to <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>' heart.'' There was light applause as the government representatives entered the church for the ceremony. They sat unsmiling as <PERSON> Colasuonno </PERSON> expressed the church's demands for more rights. `` Believers have the right to have well-prepared and educated priests'' and orders of nuns and monks need more freedom to recruit new members, the archbishop said. <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> primate, 88-year-old Cardinal <PERSON> Frantisek </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomasek </PERSON>, has taken a tougher stand with communist authorities in recent months. In January, he gave unprecedented backing to a petition demanding religious freedom. Copies of the petitions have been signed by an estimated 600,000 people in this country with a population of 15.5 million. <PERSON> Tomasek </PERSON> presided at the consecration of the two assistant bishops for his <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> archdiocese at Saturday's ceremony. After the ceremony several hundred people gathered outside <PERSON> Tomasek </PERSON>'s and chanted demands for more religious freedom. In <LOCATION> Trnava </LOCATION>, about 4,000 people were crowded into the church for the ceremony Sunday and at least 11,000 gathered outside and listened to the service carried by loudspeakers. <PERSON> Sokol </PERSON> was consecrated as a full bishop. But for the archdiocese that is normally headed by an archbihop he officially serves as an apostolic administrator.
