<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former soldiers loyal to deposed President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> raided a military armory in a failed attempt to free colleagues jailed for past coup attempts, the military said. Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Montano </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Philippine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constabulary </ORGANIZATION>, said the group got away with 24 automatic rifles in their Saturday attack. <PERSON> Montano </PERSON> said they had intended to free <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> Dulay </PERSON>, a former army colonel, provincial governor and assemblyman who was close to <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> when he was president. <PERSON> Dulay </PERSON> has been jailed at suburban Camp Crame for more than a year on charges he ordered the killing of several supporters of President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> during the 1986 presidential election that ended <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' 20-year reign. The military also announced that it filed murder and kidnapping charges against a Swede, a West German and a Filipino of German descent who were arrested in a rebel-infested area on Wednesday. They were accused of taking part in a raid by communist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas on a town southeast of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> in February. Two people were killed and two soldiers were abducted in the raid. Also Saturday, a <LOCATION> Swiss </LOCATION> judge ruled that assets held by <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> must be returned to his homeland. No figures were given, but the assets involved were believed to be a small part of the $ 1 billion that <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> officials believe <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> channeled into Swiss bank accounts before he fled to exile in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, wh