<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seventeen years after it first opened in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, `` Godspell'' has come home with its simplicity, good humor and joyous sense of wonder intact. The production, which arrived Sunday at the Lamb's Theater, is not so much a revival as a repolishing of the original material while adding bits and pieces from today's follies and foibles to bring it up to date. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is here. So are <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON>. Even Pee Wee <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> gets into the act, although he and the other names from current events are not the essential part of the story. The musical remains a carefully crafted piece of street theater that seeks to instruct if not convert. The book, devised by <PERSON> John-Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Tebelak </PERSON>, follows the Gospel According to <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON>, reinterpreting the live of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> as well as the parables he told. <PERSON> Tebelak </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> is a clown, a harlequin with a heart painted on his forehead and a big red Superman `` S'' on his chest. He's a teacher and his lessons come right from <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON>'s version of the Bible. He reinterprets many of the most famous parables such as the prodigal son. That reinterpretation is accomplished through a series of vaudeville turns directed with a sure sense of style and wit by <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON>. There's low comedy, high camp and just about every type of dumb joke in between. But the concoction works, primarily because of <PERSON> Scardino </PERSON>'s inventiveness and the exuberant score, most of it written by <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>. `` Godspell'' remains the composer's most beguiling work. <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> later went on to write such musicals as `` Pippin,'' `` The Magic Show'' and `` The Baker's Wife,'' but it is in his first show that he found the best inspiration. From an anthem like `` Prepare Ye the Way of the Lord'' to an obvious uptempo show stopper like `` We Beseech Thee,'' <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> tailored his music to a young, enthusiastic cast and still managed to produce one song, `` Day by Day,'' which found a life outside the musical. It's been fashionable to dismiss `` Godspell'' for its naivete and simple-mindedness, but this revival contains some surprising moments of power, particularly at the end of the evening when <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> is betrayed by <PERSON> Judas </PERSON>. The scene is memorable for a fine bit of acting by <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Steefel </PERSON> as the street version of the messiah and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McNeill </PERSON> as his betrayer. But then the entire cast exudes a precision and passion uncommon in most revivals. They are among some of the best young musical comedy talent around. The others include <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>, a bewitching seductress; <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON>, a sweet-faced singer; <PERSON> Trini </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarado </PERSON>, a striking woman with a low, sexy voice; <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Damaschke </PERSON>, a goofy, likable performer; <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Jemmott </PERSON>, a fine comedian and a belter as well; <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Korbich </PERSON>, a real song-and-dance hoofer; <PERSON> Mia </PERSON> <PERSON> Korf </PERSON>, who manages to make `` Day by Day'' sound fresh, and <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Perrineau </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a sturdy soul singer. The scenery by <PERSON> Allison </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> is a generic street scene, while the costumes by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolard </PERSON> are thrift-shop eccentric, making up in color what they lack in high fashion. But this resurrection of `` Godspell'' has plenty of style, high spirits and sense of fun, which make it impossible to resist. It should win plenty of new converts.
