<HEAD>Canadians Stage Nationwide Protests Over U.S.-Canada Trade Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of Canadians nationwide protested the U.S.-Canada trade bill on Sunday by lighting candles, parading in cars and stuffing phony ballot boxes with mock votes against the agreement. Several groups of demonstrators in <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> also rallied near bridges and other border crossings at <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sault </LOCATION> Ste. <PERSON> Marie </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Duluth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn </LOCATION>. Opponents of the Free Trade Agreement, which is to begin relaxing trade barriers between the nations on Jan. 1, demanded that Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> call new elections for <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> before the bill goes into effect. `` We want a vote _ now,'' demonstrators chanted on Parliament Hill in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>. Trade bill opponents also shouted `` Lyin' <PERSON> Brian </PERSON>,'' a reference to <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s 1983 statements opposing free trade between the nations. Protesters stuffed carboard boxes with mock ballots rejecting what they called `` the sell-out of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>.'' Elswhere, demonstrators sang protest songs, paraded in cars and lit candles. Protests were reported in <LOCATION> Edmonton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alberta </LOCATION>; St. <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s, <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>; and numerous cities in <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>. The protests Sunday were orchestrated by a coalition called the <ORGANIZATION> Pro-Canada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, a coalition of labor, social, women's, farm and other groups. They say the bill will sell out <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s economy, culture and social programs. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed the agreement Jan. 2. It would eliminate tariffs and reduce other barriers in nearly every facet of the $ 150 billion annual trading partnership. The changes would begin next year and be phased in during a 10-year period. The agreement, however, must be approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, and it faces staunch opposition from lawmakers in both <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> controls 208 seats in the 282-member <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION>, but public opinion polls show Canadians are sharply split on the agreement. Opposition stems from a variety of areas. <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> grape growers, for example, are upset because the agreement would eliminate an automatic 65 percent markup on U.S.-made wine. <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, the industrial and financial giant of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s 10 provinces, has also seen strong opposition to the agreement. Liberal <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Axworthy </PERSON> and New Democrat <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Langdon </PERSON> both told the <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> crowd Sunday they will continue attempts to block the government's legislation in the Commons, where the bill is up for second reading. `` We will make sure that Canadians get a full opportunity be heard,'' said <PERSON> Axworthy </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Edmonton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alberta </LOCATION>, about 100 protestors gathered at city hall and others picketed the homes of conservative ministers of Parliament.
