<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An AIDS drug can dramatically boost the intelligence of youngsters whose brains are damaged by the AIDS virus and even restores their ability to walk and talk, researchers said Sunday. Damage to the brain is one of the earliest and most devastating of the effects of the lethal virus in children. The research suggests that the drug AZT can reverse these symptoms and apparently bring virus-damaged brain cells back to health. AZT, also known as zidovudine or Retrovir, is the only medicine routinely used to suppress the AIDS virus, called HIV. In adults, it can slow the progression of AIDS but does not cure it.
</TEXT>
