<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It may look more like a coffee klatch than researchers hard at work on a new product, but that's the whole idea. The concept of group decision-making triggered by spontaneous encounters is shaping the design of a $ 75 million research and development center being built at <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the world's leading designer and manufacturer of office furniture Not only does the new seven-story, pyramid-shaped building represent a shift in <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION>'s own corporate culture; the company also hopes to market the concept of group creativeness to its customers. `` Buying new furniture and computers wo n't get people to be more productive,'' company spokesman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> said. `` Customers are coming to us with a larger agenda. They want to understand how they can work better and how their people can work better. `` But before we can be the office environment company for anyone else, we have to be it for ourselves.'' Though teamwork and spontaneous meetings are nothing new, it's unusual for a company of <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION>'s size to tinker with success The 76-year-old company had about $ 1.5 billion in sales last year. It controls about a quarter of the office furniture market, according to <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Fallucchi </PERSON>, editor and co-publisher of Facilities Design and Management, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> City-based trade magazine. The new <ORGANIZATION> Corporate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> is architecturally designed to foster communication among all levels of the organization, putting in practice the theory that spontaneous interaction is the best catalyst for creativeness. About 400 of the 8,000 workers the company employs in Grand Rapids will be moved into the building, just south of its headquarters early next year. `` We're trying to provide as many opportunities as we can in this building for people to run into one another,'' said <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Veneklasen </PERSON>, organizational environmental psychologist for <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION>. `` Research shows that 80 percent of professionals' ideas come from face-to-face communication.'' To encourage that kind of spontaneity, there are few barriers in the building; escalators are used instead of elevators -LRB- `` People never talk on elevators,'' <PERSON> Veneklasen </PERSON> said -RRB-; and four entrances to the building feed into a central meeting place, or `` town square'' in the atrium. Using what designers have dubbed the `` cave and commons'' approach, each employee will have his or her own private space, or `` cave.'' But in the middle of a circle of caves will be the group's commons area, also dubbed `` interaction nodes,'' for group meetings. Each of these areas will be equipped with a coffee and soft drink bar _ and a marker board for when the conversation turns to product ideas. `` We know that people are going to talk about the stupid neighbor's dog that kept them up all night long and they're going to diagram football plays ... But they're also going to talk about product ideas,'' <PERSON> Veneklasen </PERSON> said. `` If one product idea comes out of only one of those coffee areas, they've paid for themselves for the life of the building, given our manufacturing abilities,'' <PERSON> Veneklasen </PERSON> said. Executives will be in the directors' cluster, a ring of private offices in the middle of the building. For the `` lone rangers,'' there will be small offices without telephones or other potential distractions, <PERSON> Veneklasen </PERSON> said. There will be terraces with outdoor work areas and a fitness trail. Prairie grass will replace the traditional grass and shrubs. The company will be structured not by departments, as it is now, but by projects. All the people involved in a project, whether they be in the engineering, marketing or design departments, will be grouped together. `` At most companies, the process of developing a product is usually linear, like a relay race where the person does his part and passes it on to the next person,'' <PERSON> Veneklasen </PERSON> said. `` We're taking the rugby team approach. The designers, the engineers, the manufacturing people, the marketing people and the corporate communications people will ... pass the ball back and forth, but all going in the same direction at the same time.'' The 573,000-foot building will feature state-of-the-art laboratories for perfecting the office environment, including research on office acoustics, lighting and temperature control. <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION> has said the center will serve as a springboard for its future plans: to add 8,000 employees to its worldwide work force of 17,500 by the turn of the century. It sees the consulting service as a natural extension of its existing business, where single chairs carry price tags of up to $ 900 and big orders for major companies can run into the hundreds of thousands of dollars. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> says <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION> plans no extra charge to customers for its logistical advice. Indeed, such consulting is fast becoming a popular addition to the industry's sales pitch. `` It's not just a question of putting in a desk and a couple of file cabinets anymore,'' said <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Groot </PERSON>, communications director for <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` The aim now is to create an environment that allows office workers to take full advantage of new technology and be as productive as possible.'' But when it comes to advising clients, is <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION>'s open style for everyone? Some researchers say the concept of group creativeness, at the heart of Japanese industry, may not work in a society where individualism is king. `` It's like changing somebody's religion,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Redmon </PERSON>, an assistant professor at <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> who has been studying how well <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies are adjusting to Japanese work practices. Even for <ORGANIZATION> Steelcase </ORGANIZATION>, the team approach may make some managers uncomfortable. `` It's going to take time for everybody to get used to it,'' admitted <PERSON> Veneklasen </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
