<HEAD>Study Urges Mexico to Encourage Ties with U.S. Auto Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A study commissioned by the Mexican government says <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> should strengthen its ties to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automobile industry by making it easier to export cars assembled in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and by upgrading its auto parts industry, according to a report published Sunday. The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, which obtained the study, said it notes that a closer alliance between the two nations' auto industries might develop only if <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> distinguished itself from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and other nations competing in the market. The study, conducted by the consulting firm <ORGANIZATION> Booz-Allen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Hamilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, was commissioned last year by the Mexican government and the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> as part of efforts to obtain <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> loans for industrial restructuring. `` The Mexican government must differentiate <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> from other countries -LRB- <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> -RRB- in the eyes of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> public stressing proximity, cultural ties, common problems and the long period of constructive relationships,'' the study said. `` If <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> protectionism grows and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is lumped together with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in retaliatory <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade legislation, all of the recommendations in this report are moot,'' it said. The study estimated that salaried auto workers in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> are paid 20 percent to 25 percent of what their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> counterparts receive. The study argued that the lower costs were part of `` Mexican economic advantages within a North American auto production system -LRB- that -RRB- saves jobs for <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. workers.'' `` Without access to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, to selectively provide low-cost labor as part of the overall process, more vehicles ... and parts would be obtained from <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and various <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> countries with the consequent loss of both <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Mexican jobs,'' the study said. <PERSON> Booz-Allen </PERSON> recommended that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> immediately upgrade its auto parts-making industy, which accounted for more than half of that nation's $ 900 million auto exports trade surplus in 1986. The study also called for easing regulations on companies already assembling cars in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to encourage more exports to the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. It also recommended that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> establish a technical center in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> to keep pace with technological developments. The Big Three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers each have assembly, engine and parts plants in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> spokesmen said they were unaware of plans to increase investments there. A <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said company does n't discuss possible investments. <PERSON> Booz-Allen </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> would have to convince the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union that an automotive alliance would benefit both countries. But <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-Treasurer <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Casstevens </PERSON> said the union remained opposed to Mexican auto investments that he said exploited workers there and caused the loss of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> jobs. `` If the Mexicans develop a more competitive industry, it will mean the loss of more jobs,'' he told the News.
