<HEAD>Texaco, Icahn Face Showdown Later This Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Monday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and its biggest shareholder, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, may be headed for a showdown this week that could determine the course of their acrimonious takeover dispute. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> is waging a proxy fight for five seats on the 14-member <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> board in an effort to pressure the oil giant to let shareholders vote on his $ 60-a-share offer for the 85.2 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> stock that he does not already own. The bid values the entire company at $ 14.6 billion. The deadline for the proxy votes on the board seats is Friday when <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> plans to hold its annual shareholders meeting in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>, which is based in <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, has rejected <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s buyout proposal, and has questioned his ability to finance it Wall Street has also been skeptical about the offer. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> finished last week at $ 51.87 -LCB- a share on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has said he is so certain he could arrange the financing that he says he would put $ 300 million in escrow for payment to shareholders if he failed to arrange it by the date of the shareholder vote on the offer. Meanwhile, a published report over the weekend said court documents show an investment firm that has a large stake in <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> considered selling its stake and <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> once tried to bring in Canadian investor <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Belzberg </PERSON> to buy it. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATIO